					great king Ňörńę PrabhńĀkara, whose fame was the ornament of
					all quarters of space, whose unsurpassed store of merit had
					been obtained by the veneration of the feet of gods,
					brahmins and masters, commands all residents of the district
					of TńĀŠłĽupńĀka, starting with the governors (<foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">rńĀŠĻ£ŠĻ≠rakŇęŠĻ≠a</foreign>), as
					follows:</p><p n="12‚Äď27"> ‚ÄėBe it known to
					you that the village called CŇęyipńĀka, amidst the four
					villages ViŠł∑endi, ReŠĻÖguŠĻ≠a, KampńĀŠĻüu and Tukura, has been
					given to forty-three (Brahmins), born from families of
					teachers, of various <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">gotra</foreign>s, belonging to ńÄtharvaŠĻáika
					families, by me, after I had received a formal request, for
					the sake of acquiring merit on behalf of (his) own parents,
					from the illustrious IndrńĀdhirńĀja (‚Äėoverlord of Indra‚Äô),
					whose abundant and pure fame, spread over the surface of the
					earth, had been obtained by killing the Kumuda elephant (of
					the S/SW?) that was intoxicated as it faced the Supratńęka
					elephant (of the NW) that had been mounted (by him) for
					battle whose clatter was produced by all kings who were
					pleased at having assembled out of the desire violently to
					uproot IndrabhaŠĻ≠ŠĻ≠ńĀraka; (by IndrńĀdhirńĀja), who was the dear
					son of Mitavarman, who had more than once obtained victory
					in elephant combat, who was the moon born in the ocean which
					was the lineage of brahmins residing in MaŠĻáalkuŠłći, famous
					for giving birth to heaps of jewels of men, radiant and pure
					by the light of the good conduct and success of their famous
					ascendants ‚ÄĒ after I had made it into an <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">agrahńĀra</foreign>. It is to be
					safeguarded by all [of you], particularly by the HastikoŇõa
